Problem: Calculate the magnitude of the spin angular momentum of a proton. Give a numerical answer.  The unit of the answer should be  $10^{-35} \mathrm{~J} \mathrm{~s}$.
Solution: # Calculation of Proton Spin Angular Momentum

The magnitude of spin angular momentum is given by:
$$L_s = \hbar\sqrt{s(s+1)}$$

For a proton (spin-1/2 particle):
- $s = 1/2$
- $\hbar = 1.054571817 \times 10^{-34}$ J·s

Calculating:
$$L_s = \hbar\sqrt{\frac{1}{2}\left(\frac{1}{2}+1\right)} = \hbar\sqrt{\frac{1}{2} \times \frac{3}{2}} = \hbar\sqrt{\frac{3}{4}}$$

$$L_s = 1.054571817 \times 10^{-34} \times \frac{\sqrt{3}}{2}$$

$$L_s = 1.054571817 \times 10^{-34} \times 0.866025404$$

$$L_s = 9.1344 \times 10^{-35} \text{ J·s}$$

Converting to units of $10^{-35}$ J·s:
$$L_s = 9.1344 \text{ (in units of } 10^{-35} \text{ J·s)}$$

